#Methodology

-Used a self join on the Textbooks table to connect current textbooks to older editions
-Used LEFT JOIN to display all textbooks, including those without a prior version
-Used INNER JOIN to return only textbooks with updated versions
-Used a self join on the Authors table to connect reviewers to the authors they are reviewing
-Applied aliases to make self joins readable and easy to interpret

#Followed a structured approach:

Identify repeated relationship → Join table to itself → Apply aliases → Interpret business value

#Key Insights

-Self joins are useful when records in a table reference other records in the same table
-LEFT JOIN provides a complete view of all textbooks, even when no previous edition exists
-INNER JOIN isolates only textbooks with known older versions
-Self joining the authors table makes peer review relationships visible
--Clear aliasing is essential when working with self joins to avoid confusion

#Recommendations

-Use self joins to track textbook version history and support edition lifecycle management
-Monitor updated editions to ensure current books are being promoted to schools
-Use peer review mapping to understand editorial workflows and collaboration across authors
-Continue applying aliases consistently to improve query readability and maintainability

